clean_description: we were out for lunch at texas roadhousea simple outing like so many others but for those living with fnd theres no such thing as simple marci had just stepped out of the truck and taken a few steps toward the restaurant i looked back and immediately noticed something wasnt rightshe wasnt responding as i walked over to her her legs buckled beneath her i stepped in caught her and helped guide her safely to a nearby bench before she could fall others around us asked if we needed helpand i truly appreciated their concern i let them know we had it under control this is part of our life with functional neurological disorder episodes like these are unpredictable they happen without warning but with care awareness and support we keep moving forward we share these moments not for sympathybut to help others understand what life with fnd really looks like  fyp fyp„Ç∑  fndjourney pnes caregiverstrong invisibleillnessawareness awarenessmatters functionalneurologicaldisorder seizureawareness pnesawareness disabilityawareness chronicillnesswarrior chronicillnesssupport chronicillnesslife invisibleillnesscommunity rarediseaseawareness caregiversupport caregiverlife loveandstrength thisisfnd unseenstruggles awarenessiskey neurologicaldisorder spoonielife  fightfnd reallifewithfnd notjustinmyhead  lifewithfnd supportnotstigma strongforher friday

clean_description: venice wasnt built on solid ground it was built on millions of wooden logs driven deep into the seafloor since the year  ad this floating city has defied both time and engineering logic while most cities stand on bedrock or concrete venice rises on a forest of waterlogged timber yes  wood specifically alder trees  a type that doesnt rot underwater when buried in clay and soaked in salty water this wood doesnt decay  it petrifies over centuries it hardens becoming nearly as tough as stone a timeless wonder still holding up an entire city st marks campanile rests on  wooden piles the grand basilica della salute required over a million each pile was hammered in by hand spaced every half meter driven up to three meters deep into the seabed but why build a city on water in the early th century italy was under attack by barbarian tribes fleeing the invasions people sought refuge in the muddy marshy venetian lagoon the water was their wall  a natural fortress that enemies couldnt cross easily

clean_description: ive been seeing more and more people start weight loss meds literally weeks after giving birth and honestly it breaks my heart a little because somewhere along the way we started believing that our bodies need to snap back immediately after bringing a whole human into the world like theres something wrong with taking time to heal like softness stretch marks or a bigger size means failure and i get it the pressure is everywhere social media floods us with bounce back culture before and after photos moms who lost the baby weight in a month and youre sitting there in mesh underwear leaking from everywhere wondering whats wrong with you but let me say this loud you dont need ozempic you just had a baby you need rest nourishment patience compassion you need time to feel like you again and that has nothing to do with a scale your body isnt behind its not broken its healing adjusting protecting you and taking care of your baby  even if it doesnt look like it used to and that is more than enough so if youre feeling like youre the only one not rushing to lose weight  youre not youre human youre healing and youre doing amazing tiktokhypemoms simplysand postpartumjourney postpartumbody

clean_description: it sounds strange maybe even morbid but living with als means facing things most people never have to think about like what photo will be used when im gone recently ish took mine last november  theres a peace in it its the photo i chose not one picked in a rush not a random old memory its me now present real it means my loved ones wont have to make that choice through tears but it also broke my heart as i silently smiled through the tears i was swallowing so no one can see the pain  no one should have to do this no one should have to look into a lens and wonder how long that photo will outlive them but here i am and somehow taking control of that one small thing gave me back a little dignity in a disease that takes so much this isnt giving up this is love i have for myself for my people for the story i leave behind als livingwithals  obituaryphoto thisisals griefandhealing alsawareness alscaregiver alsadvocate alsawarenessmonth alsadvocacy viral
